# TaskFlow — Backend API

> **Stack:** Java 21 · Spring Boot 3.2 · PostgreSQL 16 · Flyway · JWT · Docker

---

## 1. Overview

TaskFlow is a RESTful task management API. Users register and log in, create projects, and manage tasks within those projects — including assigning tasks to other users, filtering by status, and setting priorities and due dates.

**Tech decisions at a glance:**

| Concern | Choice |
|---|---|
| Language | Java 21 (LTS) with virtual threads available |
| Framework | Spring Boot 3.2 — battle-tested, excellent security + data ecosystem |
| Auth | JWT (JJWT 0.12), bcrypt cost 12 |
| DB | PostgreSQL 16 with Flyway migrations |
| ORM | Spring Data JPA / Hibernate — schema validated not auto-generated |
| Tests | JUnit 5 + Testcontainers (real PostgreSQL, no mocks) |
| API collection | Bruno (`taskflow.bru` in repo root) |

---

## 2. Architecture Decisions

### Package structure — by layer, not by feature

```
com.taskflow
├── config/        # Spring beans (security, UserDetails)
├── controller/    # HTTP layer — thin, delegates to service
├── dto/           # request/ and response/ records — no entity leakage
│   ├── request/
│   └── response/
├── entity/        # JPA entities
├── exception/     # Domain exceptions + global handler
├── repository/    # Spring Data interfaces + JPQL queries
├── security/      # JwtService, JwtAuthFilter
└── service/       # Business logic — owns transactions
```

Controllers are deliberately thin: parse input, call service, return response. All authorization logic lives in the service layer, not in annotations or filters, so it's testable without HTTP.

### JWT approach

The JWT filter extracts `user_id` from the token, loads the `User` from the database, and puts it in the `SecurityContext`. This means `@AuthenticationPrincipal User caller` in controllers is a fully hydrated entity — no secondary lookups needed. The tradeoff is one extra DB read per request; acceptable for this scale and avoids stale-token issues where user state has changed.

### Flyway not auto-migrate

`spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=validate` — Hibernate validates the schema matches entities but never modifies it. Flyway owns schema changes. This is the correct approach for any production system: you get a reproducible, reviewable, rollback-capable migration history.

### Error response consistency

A `GlobalExceptionHandler` catches all exceptions in one place. Domain exceptions (`NotFoundException`, `ForbiddenException`, `ConflictException`) map to specific HTTP codes. `MethodArgumentNotValidException` produces structured field-level errors. The handler intentionally separates `401` (unauthenticated — no/bad token) from `403` (authenticated but not allowed).


## 3. Running Locally

Requires: **Docker** and **Docker Compose** only.

```bash
git clone https://github.com/ansh29verma/taskflow-Anshul
cd taskflow-[your-name]

cp .env.example .env
# Optional: edit .env to change ports or set a real JWT_SECRET

docker compose up --build
```

The API will be available at **http://localhost:8080**.

Flyway migrations run automatically on startup. The container waits for PostgreSQL to be healthy before starting.

**First request to verify it's running:**

```bash
curl http://localhost:8080/auth/login \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"email":"test@example.com","password":"password123"}'
```

---

## 4. Running Migrations

Migrations run **automatically** when the API container starts (Flyway detects pending migrations and applies them in order).

If you need to run them manually against a local database:

```bash
# With Docker Compose running:
docker compose exec api java -jar app.jar --spring.flyway.locations=classpath:db/migration
```

Migration files are in `src/main/resources/db/migration/`:

| File | Description |
|---|---|
| `V1__create_initial_schema.sql` | Users, projects, tasks tables + indexes + trigger |
| `V2__seed_test_data.sql` | Test user, 1 project, 3 tasks |
| `V1__create_initial_schema_down.sql` | Manual rollback script (not Flyway-managed) |

---

## 5. Test Credentials

Seeded by `V2__seed_test_data.sql`:

```
Email:    test@example.com
Password: password123

Email:    alice@example.com
Password: password123
```

